2. Creating a gradient with a blend mode:

```CSS
.gradient {
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background: linear-gradient(to bottom, #e74c3c, #3498db); /* Gradient from red to blue */
  mix-blend-mode: multiply;
}
```

3. Combining a blend mode with a partially transparent gradient:

```CSS
.gradient {
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(231, 76, 60, 0.5), rgba(52, 152, 219, 0.5)); /* Partially transparent gradient */
  mix-blend-mode: overlay;
}
```

4. Applying a blend mode to a box shadow:

```CSS
.box {
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  box-shadow: 0 0 20px 5px #27ae60; /* Green box shadow */
  mix-blend-mode: screen;
}
```

As you can see, blend modes can be applied to a wide range of elements to create interesting and unique effects. Experiment with different combinations to see what works best for your design.

