1. Applying a blend mode to a spinning logo:

```HTML
<div class="logo">
  <img src="logo.png">
</div>
```

```CSS
.logo {
  position: absolute;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  animation: spin 2s linear infinite;
  mix-blend-mode: screen;
}

@keyframes spin {
  0% {
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(0deg);
  }
  100% {
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(360deg);
  }
}
```

2. Applying a blend mode to moving text:

```HTML
<div class="text-container">
  <h1>Moving Text</h1>
</div>
```

```CSS
.text-container {
  position: relative;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100vh;
}

.text-container h1 {
  position: absolute;
  font-size: 5rem;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  animation: move 2s ease-in-out infinite alternate;
  mix-blend-mode: overlay;
}

@keyframes move {
  0% {
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  }
  100% {
    transform: translate(-50%, -25%);
  }
}
```

As you can see, blend modes can be applied to animate elements to create dynamic and eye-catching effects. Just be sure to consider the compatibility with different browsers and devices.

